                        <li><strong>Research methodology:</strong> Teach random sampling techniques</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <h3>Understanding Random Number Generation Technology</h3>
                    
                    <h4>Pseudorandom vs. True Random</h4>
                    <p>There are two main types of random number generators:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Pseudorandom Number Generators (PRNGs):</strong> Use mathematical algorithms to produce sequences that appear random. They are deterministic (same seed produces same sequence) but fast and suitable for most applications.</li>
                        <li><strong>True Random Number Generators (TRNGs):</strong> Use physical phenomena (atmospheric noise, radioactive decay, etc.) to generate truly random numbers. These are non-deterministic and suitable for cryptography.</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p>Our tool offers both options:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Standard Mode:</strong> Uses JavaScript's Math.random() for fast pseudorandom generation</li>
                        <li><strong>Secure Mode:</strong> Uses Web Crypto API for cryptographically secure random numbers</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <h4>Randomness Quality Indicators</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Uniform distribution:</strong> All numbers in the range should have equal probability</li>
                        <li><strong>Independence:</strong> Each generated number should be independent of previous numbers</li>
                        <li><strong>Unpredictability:</strong> Future numbers cannot be predicted from past numbers</li>
                        <li><strong>Period length:</strong> How long before the sequence repeats (for PRNGs)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <h3>Best Practices for Using Random Numbers</h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Choose the right generator:</strong> Use pseudorandom for simulations, true random for security</li>
                        <li><strong>Set appropriate ranges:</strong> Ensure your range covers all possible values you need</li>
                        <li><strong>Check for uniqueness:</strong> Enable unique numbers when duplicates are not allowed</li>
                        <li><strong>Validate results:</strong> Use statistics to verify randomness properties</li>
                        <li><strong>Seed properly:</strong> When using pseudorandom generators, use appropriate seeds</li>
                        <li><strong>Test extensively:</strong> Test your random number usage with edge cases</li>
                        <li><strong>Document your process:</strong> Record settings for reproducibility</li>
                    </ol>
                    
                    <h3 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
                    <div class="faq-section">
                        <div class="faq-item">
                            <div class="faq-question">
                                <span>What's the difference between pseudorandom and truly random numbers?</span>
                                <span class="expand-icon">‚ñº</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="faq-answer">
                                <p><strong>Pseudorandom numbers</strong> are generated by mathematical algorithms and appear random but are deterministic (same seed produces same sequence). <strong>Truly random numbers</strong> come from physical processes and are non-deterministic. For most applications, pseudorandom is sufficient, but cryptography requires true randomness.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-item">
                            <div class="faq-question">
                                <span>How does the "cryptographically secure" option work?</span>
                                <span class="expand-icon">‚ñº</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="faq-answer">
                                <p>When you enable cryptographically secure mode, the tool uses the Web Crypto API's <code>crypto.getRandomValues()</code> method, which generates random numbers suitable for cryptographic applications. These numbers are generated from secure entropy sources available in your browser or operating system.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-item">
                            <div class="faq-question">
                                <span>Can I generate negative random numbers?</span>
                                <span class="expand-icon">‚ñº</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="faq-answer">
                                <p>Yes, simply set a negative minimum value. For example, setting minimum to -100 and maximum to 100 will generate numbers between -100 and 100 inclusive.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-item">
                            <div class="faq-question">
                                <span>What happens if I request more unique numbers than the range allows?</span>
                                <span class="expand-icon">‚ñº</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="faq-answer">
                                <p>If you request more unique numbers than are possible within your specified range (e.g., 10 unique numbers from range 1-5), the tool will generate all possible numbers within the range and then show a warning message. The "Unique Numbers Only" option will be automatically disabled in such cases.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-item">
                            <div class="faq-question">
                                <span>How random are the generated numbers?</span>
                                <span class="expand-icon">‚ñº</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="faq-answer">
                                <p>In standard mode, numbers come from JavaScript's Math.random() which uses a pseudorandom algorithm with approximately uniform distribution. In secure mode, numbers come from cryptographic sources and are suitable for security-sensitive applications. Our statistics panel helps you verify the randomness of generated sequences.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="faq-item">
                            <div class="faq-question">
                                <span>Can I use this tool for lottery number generation?</span>
                                <span class="expand-icon">‚ñº</span>
                            </div>
